[rule of the nouns in -ros ;
 siro/s , ‘silo’ or pit for storing corn]:
One of the ‘Sillographers’ or writers of lampoons writes the first syllable long, maybe lengthening it, methinks because of the r . The Sillographers are Xenophanes, Timon, and some others.

The word to/nos ( lit. a stretching) is used of sound in the epithet seven-toned applied to the lyre, for instance by Terpander and Ion. The former says: (fr. 5), Lyra Graeca i. p. 32 and the latter:

Eleven-stringad Lyre with thy flight of ten steps into the place where the three concordant roads of Harmonia meet, i.e. with the ten musical ‘intervals’ given by the conjunction of the three tetrachords;
 lit. to the harmonious crossways (three-roads) of H. (metaph. from the crossways of Hecate?) once all the Greeks raised but a meagre music, playing thee seven-toned four by four i.e. the combination of two tetrachords into the 7-note scale [but now ...]. CURFRAG.tlg-0308.3
